isi

We fitted a linear mixed model (estimated using REML and nloptwrap optimizer) to predict isi with group and time_point (formula: isi ~ 1 + group + time_point + group * time_point). The model included login_id as random effect (formula: ~1 | login_id). The model’s total explanatory power is substantial (conditional R2 = 0.56) and the part related to the fixed effects alone (marginal R2) is of 0.27. The model’s intercept, corresponding to group = control and time_point = 1st , is at 13.53 (S.E. = 0.28, p < .001, 95% CI [12.99, 14.07]). Within this model:

  • The effect of group [treatment] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -0.13, S.E. = 0.39, p = 0.742, 95% CI [-0.89, 0.64]; Std. beta = -0.03, 95% CI [-0.20, 0.15])
  • The effect of time point [2nd] is statistically significant and negative (beta = -2.53, S.E. = 0.33, p < .001, 95% CI [-3.18, -1.89]; Std. beta = -0.58, 95% CI [-0.73, -0.43])
  • The effect of time point [3rd] is statistically significant and negative (beta = -2.41, S.E. = 0.59, p < .001, 95% CI [-3.56, -1.25]; Std. beta = -0.55, 95% CI [-0.81, -0.29])
  • The interaction effect of time point [2nd] on group [treatment] is statistically significant and negative (beta = -2.98, S.E. = 0.49, p < .001, 95% CI [-3.95, -2.02]; Std. beta = -0.68, 95% CI [-0.90, -0.46])
  • The interaction effect of time point [3rd] on group [treatment] is statistically significant and negative (beta = -3.73, S.E. = 0.83, p < .001, 95% CI [-5.35, -2.10]; Std. beta = -0.85, 95% CI [-1.22, -0.48])

Standardized parameters were obtained by fitting the model on a standardized version of the dataset. 95% Confidence Intervals (CIs) and p-values were computed using a Wald normal distribution approximation.
